HEADWORD: Preconization
<hw>Pre*con`i*za"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praeconium</ets> a crying out in public, fr. <ets>praeco</ets>,
<ets>-onis</ets>, a crier, a herald: cf. F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧conisation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A publishing by
proclamation; a public proclamation.</def> <rj><au>Bp.
Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>A formal approbation by the pope
of a person nominated to an ecclesiastical dignity.</def> <rj><au>Addis
& Arnold.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preconize</ent>⟦br⟧
